@{header}
left: Građevinar 1/2018
right: Ivica Kožar, Tea Rukavina, Adnan Ibrahimbegović
barside: left
color: #F27835
textcolor: #FDFDFD
rightcolor: #F27835
linecolor: #F27835
@{end header}

@{columns 2}

@{column}
@{markdown}
A finite element computer code has been developed in *Mathematica* [18] and FEAP [19] to implement and validate the model. The chosen example is a cantilever bar clamped at the left-hand side, with the displacement ū imposed at the right-hand side (see Figure 7). The bar is discretized by two finite elements, where the material model for element 1 is softening damage, while it is linear elasticity for element 2. The geometric and material properties used in this example are: E = 1000, σ_f = 150, K̄ = −200, L = 1 and A = 1. The imposed displacement is equal to ū = 0.75.
@{end markdown}

@{figure}
src: jce-images/image44.png
caption: Figure 7. Cantilever bar with imposed displacement
width: 80%
@{end figure}

@{markdown}
The global response of the structure is shown in Figure 8. The behaviour of the bar is linear elastic until the elasticity limit is reached. Then the softening starts and the crack opens in the middle of element 1. That means that all the stress is concentrated at the discontinuity, while the bulk of the material is unloading. If we unload the bar, the diagram goes back to zero, showing the typical behaviour of damage models. It can be seen that the unloading and the reloading follow the same path and, in the end, the bar reaches complete failure, σ = 0.
@{end markdown}

@{figure}
src: jce-images/image45.png
caption: Figure 8. Force-displacement diagram with two loading-unloading cycles
width: 80%
@{end figure}

@{column}

@{end columns}

